04008nam a22006735i 9781501735011DE-B159720191126113341.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191126s2019    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017350117 a10.7591/97815017350112doi  a(DE-B1597)534131  a(OCoLC)1129161942  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0060002bisacsh1 aHernadi, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCultural Transactions :bNature, Self, Society /cPaul Hernadi. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (144 p.) :b3 drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tPrologue: Enticements and Forewarnings -- tChapter One. How to Do, Make, and Mean Things with Words -- tChapter Two. The Performance, Recording, and Mental Rehearsal of Cultural Transactions -- tChapter Three. Who We Are: The Rhetoric, Grammar, and Logic of Communal Identities -- tChapter Four. Society, Nature, Selves: Freedom and Diversity -- tChapter Five. Four More Triads and Beyond -- tEpilogue: Loose Ends and Afterthoughts -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this provocative book, Paul Hernadi goes beyond current intersubjectivist approaches to cultural phenomena, maintaining instead that the natural, the personal, and the social are complementary dimensions of all human making, doing, and meaning. His chief concern is with verbal communication, but he also considers music and architecture, cooking and business, television and film, basketball and chess.For centuries, Hernadi notes, people viewed either matter or mind-nature or spirit-as the ultimate principle of being and becoming. In contrast, much contemporary theory assumes that reality is socially constructed. While recognizing the powers of culture, Hernadi pays close attention to the material conditions and personal responsibilities of human agency as well. Tracing both continuities and disruptions in key intellectual traditions, he relates his conceptions of culture, existence, and experience to three classic triads: the rhetorical aims of moving, delighting, and teaching; the psychological capacities of willing, feeling, and knowing; and the evaluative criteria of justice, beauty, and truth.Discussing such controversies as the conflict between Lacanian and Derridean viewpoints, this book will be essential reading for anyone interested in literary theory, feminist theory, and the intersections of psychoanalysis and philosophy in literary criticism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 4aGender Studies. 4aPsychology & Psychiatry. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501735011423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501735011.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG